Sequim ([/ˈskwɪm/](/Help:IPA/English)&#32; [ⓘ](/File:En-us-Sequim.ogg) SKWIM ) is a city in [Clallam County, Washington](/Clallam_County,_Washington), United States. It is located on the north side of the [Olympic Peninsula](/Olympic_Peninsula) between the [Dungeness River](/Dungeness_River) and [Sequim Bay](/Sequim_Bay). The city is south of the [Strait of Juan de Fuca](/Strait_of_Juan_de_Fuca) and north of the [Olympic Mountains](/Olympic_Mountains). The population was 8,024 as of the [2020 census](/2020_United_States_Census); &#91;3&#93; the estimated population in 2023 was 8,203. Sequim is connected to nearby [Port Angeles](/Port_Angeles,_Washington) by [U.S. Route 101](/U.S._Route_101_in_Washington), which runs south of the city's downtown.

The city lies within the [rain shadow](/Rain_shadow) of the Olympic Mountains and receives, on average, less than 16 inches (410&#160;mm) of rain per year – about the same as [Los Angeles, California](/Los_Angeles,_California) – giving rise to the region's local nickname of Sunny Sequim . However, the city is relatively close to some of the wettest [temperate rainforests](/Temperate_rainforest) of the [contiguous United States](/Contiguous_United_States). This climate anomaly is sometimes called the "Blue Hole of Sequim". &#91;5&#93; Fogs and cool breezes from the Strait of Juan de Fuca make Sequim's climate more humid than would be expected from the low average rate of annual precipitation.

Sequim and the surrounding area are particularly known for the commercial cultivation of [lavender](/Lavender), supported by the unique climate. The city is nicknamed the "Lavender Capital of North America". The area is also known for its [Dungeness crab](/Dungeness_crab), named for the nearby [Dungeness Spit](/Dungeness_Spit).

Etymology

The name Sequim is derived from the [Klallam](/Klallam_language) word sxʷčkʷíyəŋ , &#91;6&#93; which means "hunting ground" &#91;7&#93; or "place for going to shoot". &#91;8&#93; It was adopted as the name of the settlement in 1879, with the spelling replacing the earlier "Seguim". &#91;9&#93; The historic translation of "quiet waters" was disproven in 2010 by linguist [Timothy Montler](/Timothy_Montler), who had researched the Klallam language and interviewed elders of the [Jamestown S'Klallam Tribe](/Jamestown_S%27Klallam_Tribe_of_Washington). &#91;10&#93; Sequim is pronounced as one syllable, with the e elided: "skwim"; a common mispronounciation is "see-kwim". &#91;9&#93; &#91;11&#93;

History

Indigenous inhabitants

Fossils discovered in the late 1970s – at a dig near Sequim known as the [Manis Mastodon site](/Manis_Mastodon_site), by Carl Gustafson, an archaeologist at [Washington State University](/Washington_State_University) – included a [mastodon](/Mastodon) bone with an embedded bone point, evidencing the presence of hunters in the area about 14,000 years ago. According to Michael R. Waters, an archaeologist at [Texas A&M University](/Texas_A%26M_University), this is the first hunting weapon found that dates to the pre-[Clovis](/Clovis_culture) period.

The [S'Klallam](/Klallam) tribe had inhabited the region prior to the arrival of the first Europeans. S'Klallam means "the strong people". The band of S'Klallam Indians disbanded into their own individual federally recognized tribes in the early 1900s. The local tribe is the Jamestown S'Klallam tribe, named after one of their early leaders, Lord James Balch. According to other tales, the town Sequim in S'Klallam means "a place for going to shoot", which represents the abundance of game and wildlife of the area. &#91;12&#93; &#91;13&#93; Archeological excavation during construction of the [U.S. Route 101](/U.S._Route_101_in_Washington) bypass in the 1990s found artifacts that were dated between 6000 to 8000 years [before present](/Before_present). &#91;14&#93;

Settlement

[Manuel Quimper](/Manuel_Quimper) and [George Vancouver](/George_Vancouver) explored the region's coast in the 1790s. The first European settlers arrived in the Dungeness Valley in the 1850s, settling nearby [Dungeness, Washington](/Dungeness,_Washington). While the lands along the river became fertile farmlands, the remainder of the area remained arid prairie, known as "the desert". &#91;5&#93; Irrigation canals first brought water to the prairie in the 1890s, allowing the expansion of farmlands.

Sequim was officially incorporated on October 31, 1913. For many decades small farms, mostly dairy farms, dotted the area around the small town. Near the end of World War I, Sequim became a stop for a railway that passed through from [Port Angeles](/Port_Angeles) to [Port Townsend](/Port_Townsend), built primarily to carry wood products from the forests of the western [Olympic Peninsula](/Olympic_Peninsula).

Geography

View of Sequim and the Dungeness River area from the [International Space Station](/International_Space_Station)

According to the [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), the city has a total area of 6.37 square miles (16.50&#160;km 2 ), of which 6.31 square miles (16.34&#160;km 2 ) is land and 0.06 square miles (0.16&#160;km 2 ) is water. &#91;15&#93;

The forests around Sequim are dominated by [Douglas-fir](/Douglas-fir) and [western red cedar](/Western_red_cedar). Other trees growing in the area include [black cottonwood](/Black_cottonwood), [red alder](/Red_alder), [bigleaf maple](/Bigleaf_maple), [Pacific madrone](/Pacific_madrone), [lodgepole pine](/Lodgepole_pine) and [Garry oak](/Garry_oak), all of which can grow to a significant size. Historically, much of the area was an open, oak-studded prairie, supported by somewhat excessively-drained gravelly and sandy loam soil; agriculture and development of the Dungeness valley have changed this ecosystem. Most soils under Sequim have been placed in a series that is named after the city. &#91;16&#93; This "Sequim series" is one of the few [Mollisols](/Mollisol) in western Washington and its high [base saturation](/Base_saturation), a characteristic of the Mollisol order, is attributed to the minimal leaching of bases caused by low annual rainfall. &#91;17&#93;

Sequim is home to a herd of [Roosevelt elk](/Roosevelt_elk). The herd occasionally crosses U.S. Route 101 just to the southeast of the town. Radio collars on some members of the herd trigger warning lights for motorists. &#91;18&#93;

Climate

Sequim experiences a [warm-summer Mediterranean climate](/Warm-summer_Mediterranean_climate) ([Köppen climate classification](/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification) Csb ), sometimes classified as an oceanic climate owing to the relatively cool temperatures. Sequim is in the [rain shadow](/Rain_shadow) of the [Olympic Mountains](/Olympic_Mountains), so annual precipitation is the lowest in the western portion of the state at only 16 inches,
Winters are mostly mild with very little snowfall. Many years there is no snow at all. The highest temperature recorded in Sequim was 99&#160;°F (37.2&#160;°C) on July 16, 1941, and the lowest −3&#160;°F (−19.4&#160;°C) on January 19, 1935 and February 4, 1989. &#91;19&#93;

