2020 census

As of the [2020 census](/2020_United_States_census), there were 8,018 people and 3,480 households in the city. The [population density](/Population_density) was 1,269.8 inhabitants per square mile (490.3/km 2 ). The racial makeup of the city was 86.7% [White](/White_(U.S._Census)), 1.9% [African American](/African_American_(U.S._Census)), 0.9% [Native American](/Native_American_(U.S._Census)), 3.1% [Asian](/Asian_(U.S._Census)), 0.0% [Pacific Islander](/Race_(U.S._Census)), and 6.1% from two or more races. [Hispanic](/Hispanic_(U.S._Census)) or [Latino](/Latino_(U.S._Census)) people of any race were 8.5% of the population. &#91;3&#93;

19.3% of residents were under the age of 18; and 34.0% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 44.7% male and 55.3% female. &#91;3&#93;

2010 census

As of the [2010 census](/2010_United_States_census), there were 6,606 people, 3,340 households, and 1,626 families residing in the city. The [population density](/Population_density) was 1,046.9 inhabitants per square mile (404.2/km 2 ). There were 3,767 housing units at an average density of 597.0 per square mile (230.5/km 2 ). The racial makeup of the city was 91.3% [White](/White_(U.S._Census)), 0.4% [African American](/African_American_(U.S._Census)), 1.2% [Native American](/Native_American_(U.S._Census)), 1.9% [Asian](/Asian_(U.S._Census)), 0.1% [Pacific Islander](/Race_(U.S._Census)), 1.7% from [other races](/Race_(U.S._Census)), and 3.2% from two or more races. [Hispanic](/Hispanic_(U.S._Census)) or [Latino](/Latino_(U.S._Census)) people of any race were 4.8% of the population.

There were 3,340 households, of which 17.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 36.5% were [married couples](/Marriage) living together, 9.4% had a female householder with no husband present, 2.8% had a male householder with no wife present, and 51.3% were non-families. 45.5% of all households were made up of individuals, and 29.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 1.87 and the average family size was 2.57.

The median age in the city was 57.9 years. 15.2% of residents were under the age of 18; 6.3% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 15.9% were from 25 to 44; 22.1% were from 45 to 64; and 40.4% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 44.4% male and 55.6% female.

Economy

The [U.S. Department of Energy](/United_States_Department_of_Energy) maintains a marine laboratory on Sequim Bay that is operated by the [Pacific Northwest National Laboratory](/Pacific_Northwest_National_Laboratory). &#91;23&#93; [Mervin Manufacturing](/Mervin_Manufacturing), a producer of [snowboards](/Snowboard), has a 60,000-square-foot (5,600&#160;m 2 ) factory in Sequim that opened in 1995. &#91;24&#93;

Tourism

Drawing of a mastodon skeleton by [Rembrandt Peale](/Rembrandt_Peale)

The [Dungeness National Wildlife Refuge](/Dungeness_National_Wildlife_Refuge) is located just north of the city, near the mouth of the [Dungeness River](/Dungeness_River). It includes the [Dungeness Spit](/Dungeness_Spit) and a five-mile (8&#160;km) hike to the New Dungeness Lighthouse &#91;25&#93; at the end of the spit.
To the east along U.S. Route 101 is Sequim Bay, a 4-mile (6.5&#160;km) long inlet from the Strait of Juan de Fuca. Along the western stretch is the [Sequim Bay State Park](/Sequim_Bay_State_Park). The inlet is a popular birdwatching area. &#91;26&#93;

The [Museum and Arts Center](/Museum_and_Arts_Center,_Sequim,_Washington) features both natural and cultural exhibits, including a mastodon mural mounted with the remaining mastodon bones, artifacts, and a video on the [excavation](/Excavation_(archaeology)).

Government

Sequim's [city hall](/City_hall)

Sequim has had a [council–manager government](/Council%E2%80%93manager_government) since a 1995 referendum was approved by city residents. The [city council](/City_council) has seven members who each serve a four-year term and are elected [at-large](/At-large). The city council appoints a ceremonial [mayor](/Mayor) to preside over meetings during a two-year term and approves the hiring of a [city manager](/City_manager) as head of the municipal government's departments. &#91;27&#93; Councilmember Brandon Janisse was elected as mayor in January 2024. &#91;28&#93; Matt Huish has been the city manager since his hiring in November 2021. &#91;29&#93;

At the federal level, the city lies within the [6th congressional district](/Washington%27s_6th_congressional_district), which encompasses the entire Olympic Peninsula, the neighboring [Kitsap Peninsula](/Kitsap_Peninsula), and part of [Tacoma](/Tacoma,_Washington). &#91;30&#93; &#91;31&#93; Sequim is part of the state's [24th legislative district](/Washington%27s_24th_legislative_district), which includes most of the Olympic Peninsula except for [Mason County](/Mason_County,_Washington). &#91;32&#93; The city is represented in the Clallam County Commission as part of the 1st district, which includes most areas east of the Dungeness River. &#91;33&#93;

Arts and culture

Festivals and events

Sequim holds its annual Irrigation Festival in early May. It was first held on May 1, 1896, to commemorate the first anniversary of an irrigation system on the Dungeness River and is the longest continually running festival in the state, reaching its 130th edition in 2025. The festival includes a street parade, concerts, live entertainment and performances, [arts and crafts](/Arts_and_crafts), a [car show](/Car_show), and a [fashion show](/Fashion_show) for clothing made with recycled materials. &#91;34&#93; &#91;35&#93;

Other annual festivals include the Sunshine Festival, which began in 2020 and is held in March, &#91;36&#93; &#91;37&#93; and the Sequim Lavender Weekend, held in July since 1997. &#91;38&#93;

Library

The city is part of the [North Olympic Library System](/North_Olympic_Library_System) (NOLS), which serves Clallam County. Sequim had its own library that was established in the 1910s and moved into the Clyde Rhodefer Memorial Library in 1936. The new library, named for the first Clallam County casualty in [World War I](/World_War_I), was opened in November 1936 and was constructed by the federal [Public Works Administration](/Public_Works_Administration). &#91;39&#93; The Clallam County Rural Library District, the predecessor to NOLS, acquired the branch in 1947. It was replaced with a modern building near Sequim High School in 1983. &#91;40&#93; The Sequim branch later became too small for the growing city and was proposed for replacement in a 2001 study; it was renovated in 2009 and a replacement was to be funded by a [bond measure](/Bond_measure) in 2018 that failed to pass with the required supermajority. &#91;41&#93; The state government awarded a grant in 2020 for the replacement library project, which broke ground in 2024. It is scheduled to open in 2025 and cost $10.6&#160;million; funding from the state government was supplemented by private donations. &#91;42&#93; &#91;43&#93;

Education

The Sequim School District provides public [K–12 education](/K%E2%80%9312_education) to pupils in the city and surrounding area, which includes a portion of northeastern [Jefferson County](/Jefferson_County,_Washington). &#91;44&#93; During the 2023–24 school year, the district had 2,613 total students and 145 teachers or instructors. &#91;45&#93; It has one high school, one middle school, two elementary schools, and one [alternative school](/Alternative_education). &#91;46&#93; &#91;47&#93;

A private school, the [Five Acre School](/Five_Acre_School), was established in 1995 at a rural property near Sequim and holds classes for students through the sixth grade. It became a non-profit organization in 2019. &#91;48&#93; &#91;49&#93;

Media

Film and television

Due to a social media post, students from the [rotary club](/Rotary_International) of Sequim High School were able to procure a film screening of [The Boys in the Boat](/The_Boys_in_the_Boat_(film)), a movie centered around [Joe Rantz](/Joe_Rantz) and his gold-medal [1936 Summer Olympics](/Rowing_at_the_1936_Summer_Olympics) rowing team. The 2023 motion picture, directed by [George Clooney](/George_Clooney), was planned to be shown at a school auditorium as the city lacks a formal movie theater. &#91;50&#93; A number of students from the school district were in invited attendance at the premiere in December 2023, held at the [SIFF Cinema Downtown](/SIFF_Cinema_Downtown) in Seattle. &#91;51&#93;

Newspapers

The former offices of the [Sequim Gazette](/Sequim_Gazette)

A local newspaper, the [Sequim Gazette](/Sequim_Gazette) , is owned by [Sound Publishing](/Sound_Publishing) and publishes weekly print editions on Wednesdays that are delivered to subscribers. &#91;52&#93; Its sister newspaper [Peninsula Daily News](/Peninsula_Daily_News) , based in Port Angeles, also covers the area and has daily print editions. &#91;53&#93; The city's earliest newspaper, the Sequim Press , was founded in 1911 and ceased publication in 1985. The Gazette was originally known as the Sequim Shopper when it began publication in January 1974 and was renamed later that year to the Jimmy Come Lately Gazette . The newspaper was renamed to the Sequim Gazette on April 4, 1990, and was owned by Olympic View Publishing until it was sold to Sound Publishing in 2011. &#91;54&#93; &#91;55&#93;

Radio

Sequim is served by local radio stations based in the city and nearby Port Angeles, as well as broadcasts from [Victoria, British Columbia](/Victoria,_British_Columbia). Non-commercial station [KSQM](/KSQM) debuted in 2009 and broadcasts [community programming](/Community_radio) as well as music. &#91;56&#93; A commercial classic rock station, [KZEG](/KZEG_(FM)), went on the air in 2018 and was originally named KZQM. &#91;57&#93;

Infrastructure

Transportation

Sequim is connected to nearby Port Angeles and other areas of the Olympic Peninsula by [U.S. Route 101](/U.S._Route_101_in_Washington), a major highway that travels around most of the peninsula. &#91;58&#93; The highway uses a 4-mile (6.4&#160;km) [bypass](/Bypass_(road)) around the south side of the city's downtown with three interchanges. The bypass opened to traffic in August 1999 following several decades of planning to alleviate traffic congestion through Sequim. &#91;59&#93; It cost $40.7&#160;million (equivalent to $71.8&#160;million in 2024 dollars) &#91;60&#93; to construct and included the installation of [warning signals](/Warning_signal) triggered by the presence of nearby [Roosevelt elk](/Roosevelt_elk) wearing [radio collars](/Wildlife_radio_telemetry) for tracking. &#91;18&#93; &#91;61&#93;

The city is also served by [Clallam Transit](/Clallam_Transit), a local [fare-free](/Free_public_transport) &#91;62&#93; bus system that connects Sequim to Port Angeles, Blyn, and Diamond Point. &#91;63&#93; &#91;64&#93; It also operates a [microtransit](/Microtransit) service within the city. &#91;65&#93; The agency operates intercity service to [Poulsbo](/Poulsbo,_Washington) and [Bainbridge Island](/Bainbridge_Island,_Washington) ferry terminal on the Strait Shot, a route it launched in 2017 and still charges fares. &#91;62&#93; &#91;66&#93; Additional intercity service to [Edmonds](/Edmonds,_Washington) and [Seattle](/Seattle) is provided by the Dungeness Line, a private bus line operated by [Greyhound](/Greyhound_Lines) and partially funded by the state's [Travel Washington](/Travel_Washington) program. &#91;67&#93;

A private airfield, named [Sequim Valley Airport](/Sequim_Valley_Airport), was built northwest of the city near Carlsborg in 1983. The area was chosen for its dry climate and level terrain; a paved runway was added in 1986. The airport is primarily used for [general aviation](/General_aviation) and also hosts flight instructors, [hot air balloon](/Hot_air_balloon) flights, air cargo, and emergency services. It is the site of the annual Olympic Peninsula Air Affaire/Fly-In, a [fly-in](/Fly-in) festival. &#91;68&#93;

Utilities

Electric power for Sequim residents and businesses is provided by the Clallam County Public Utility District (PUD), a public utility that serves most of the county. Most of its electricity is purchased from the federal [Bonneville Power Administration](/Bonneville_Power_Administration) and is derived primarily from hydroelectric dams on the [Columbia](/Columbia_River) and [Snake](/Snake_River) rivers. &#91;69&#93; The PUD constructed a 30-kilowatt community [solar array](/Solar_array) at its former Sequim [substation](/Electrical_substation) in 2019 and offered direct purchases for consumers. &#91;70&#93; It is planned to be expanded with a [microgrid](/Microgrid) demonstration project funded with a grant from the [Washington State Department of Commerce](/Washington_State_Department_of_Commerce). &#91;71&#93;

The city government provides [tap water](/Tap_water) from three sources: an [infiltration gallery](/Infiltration_gallery) on the Dungeness River and two groundwater [wells](/Well). Sequim has three [reservoirs](/Reservoir) that hold a combined 2.9&#160;million US gallons (11,000,000&#160;L) that is treated and chlorinated before use. &#91;72&#93; &#91;73&#93; The city maintains 72 miles (116&#160;km) of pipes and provides approximately 800,000 US gallons (3,000,000&#160;L) of water per day. &#91;74&#93; The infiltration gallery was constructed in 1953 to replace a direct feed from the Dungeness River. &#91;75&#93; &#91;76&#93; The city government also operates a [sewage](/Sewage) system that collects wastewater with 73 miles (117&#160;km) of sewer lines that lead to a [sewage treatment plant](/Sewage_treatment_plant) that processes up to 1.67&#160;million US gallons (6,300,000&#160;L) per day. &#91;77&#93; &#91;78&#93; The wastewater is separated into reclaimed water, used for other city projects, and biosolids that are used on [hay](/Hay) fields; a portion of the treated water is also discharged into the Strait of Juan de Fuca through an [outfall](/Outfall) pipe off the coast. &#91;79&#93; The sewage system also serves the unincorporated [Carlsborg](/Carlsborg,_Washington) area under a contract with Clallam County and the [Jamestown S'Klallam Tribe](/Jamestown_S%27Klallam_Tribe_of_Washington)'s facilities in Blyn per a 2018 agreement. &#91;80&#93;

Sequim contracts with Olympic Disposal, a subsidiary of [Waste Connections](/Waste_Connections), to provide curbside pickup of [garbage](/Municipal_solid_waste), [recycling](/Single-stream_recycling), and [yard waste](/Yard_waste) from residents and businesses. &#91;81&#93;

Healthcare

The city lies within the [public hospital](/Public_hospital) district for [Olympic Medical Center](/Olympic_Medical_Center), which has its main facilities in Port Angeles and serves most of Clallam County. &#91;82&#93; Olympic Medical Center operates several [clinics](/Medical_clinic) in Sequim, including a walk-in facility for non-emergency care and specialty facilities in the city. &#91;83&#93; In 2022, the Jamestown S'Klallam Tribe opened an opioid treatment center in Sequim to serve its tribal citizens and other members of the community. The tribe plans to also construct a [psychiatric hospital](/Psychiatric_hospital) using funds from the state government. &#91;84&#93; &#91;85&#93;

